8.1
int *p = {10,20,20};

cout << *p;

p++;

cout << *p;
This will show an error since we have allocated the pointer and not assigned memory for it in heap.
8.2
v1
int arr[] = {10,20,30};

cout << *arr;

cout << arr;

arr++;

cout << *arr;
The issue with this code is that we are doing arr++. it is not valid in cpp.
To solve it we need to declare a pointer and use it.
